mt_raw:
The Financial Secretary, with the assistance of the Director of the Financial Services and Treasury Bureau, is responsible for policies to maintain the stability and integrity of Hong Kong’s financial system and to maintain Hong Kong’s status as an international financial centre. To implement these policies, the responsibilities of the Financial Secretary for Financial Administration include:
- promoting the overall stability and effective operation of the banking system;
- working with other relevant institutions and organisations to develop the debt market;
- handling matters relating to the issuance and circulation of legal banknotes and coins;
- promoting the safety and efficiency of financial infrastructure by developing payment, clearing and settlement systems, and operating such systems where appropriate; and
- working with other relevant institutions and organisations to promote confidence in Hong Kong’s monetary and financial systems, and implementing appropriate market development measures to help strengthen the international competitiveness of Hong Kong’s financial services.

The monetary base (Table 1) includes:
- Liability Certificates (which provide full backing for banknotes issued by the three note-issuing banks);
- Banknotes and coins in circulation issued by the government;
- The aggregate balance of settlement accounts at the HKMA (i.e. the Aggregate Balance); and
- Exchange Fund Bills and Notes issued by the HKMA on behalf of the government.

The HKMA’s Fintech Facilitation Office continued to work with various banking sectors to implement the “Fintech 2025” strategy, promote wider adoption of fintech in the industry, and enhance Hong Kong’s position as a fintech hub in Asia. The key measures implemented during the year included:
- Promoting the application of Regtech and conducting fintech application assessments;
- Advancing work on wholesale central bank digital currency to improve cross-border payments;
- Deepening research on the issuance of retail central bank digital currency (i.e. “e-HKD”) in Hong Kong;
- Launching the Commercial Data Pipeline;
- Strengthening talent development;
- Leveraging resources to support the fintech ecosystem through policy measures;
- Strengthening cross-border fintech cooperation; and
- Promoting wider use of the Faster Payment System (FPS).

The Exchange Fund Advisory Committee has set the following investment objectives for the Exchange Fund:
(i) to preserve capital;
(ii) to ensure that the overall monetary base is fully backed by highly liquid US dollar assets at all times;
(iii) to ensure that liquidity is sufficient to maintain monetary and financial stability; and
(iv) to achieve investment returns, within the constraints of (i) to (iii) above, to preserve the long-term purchasing power of the Exchange Fund.

The audit procedures performed in relation to the valuation of financial assets and financial liabilities measured at fair value included:
- Understanding the valuation processes for different categories of financial assets and financial liabilities, including related monitoring controls;
- Evaluating and testing monitoring controls, including relevant application controls in computer systems;
- Obtaining confirmations on the valuation, existence, rights and obligations, and completeness of financial assets and financial liabilities;
- Verifying prices against independent sources if market quotations were used;
- If the valuation technique used inputs based on observable market data, evaluating whether the valuation technique was appropriate and whether the assumptions used were reasonable, and verifying the inputs against independent sources; and
- If the valuation technique used inputs not based on observable market data, evaluating whether the valuation technique was appropriate and whether the assumptions and inputs used were reasonable.
